2026-04-16 12:14:07 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Output Cable (+) to load module', 'Control Output Cable (−) to load module'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show that, when the switch is ON, the conductor labeled Control Output Cable (−) is actually at +11.98 V relative to the conductor labeled Control Output Cable (+). Therefore the control module’s output polarity is reversed with respect to the intended labeling. At the load, the conductor going to the series diode and lamps (the intended +12 V input) is wired to Control Output Cable (+), and the return is wired to Control Output Cable (−). Because the control outputs are effectively swapped, the load sees 0 V on its diode input and +12 V on its return, so the series diode is reverse-biased and the lamp never energizes. The repair should swap the two control-to-load conductors so that the physical line carrying +12 V from the control module (currently on Control Output Cable (−)) is reconnected to the load’s +12 V/diode input, and the 0 V line (currently on Control Output Cable (+)) is connected to the load’s return. This configuration error of the two output cables is the remaining root cause preventing lamp operation.'
